english:
  title: Epitaph and Preface for the Joint Burial of Master Kim, Director of the Board of Appointments and Concurrent Censor, and His Wife, Lady Lee
  author: Kwon O-bok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Kim's courtesy name was Meng, his personal name Zi-jin. He was from Gimhae, descendant of King Suro, founder of Gaya. His father, of the name Keuk-il, served his parents without seeking office and was honored with a gateway of filial piety. His mother was Lady Lee, daughter of the Provincial Governor of Seoul.

    Born in the eighth month of the first day of Yongle's Gyeonggin year, from childhood he devoted himself to letters, gaining renown throughout the southern provinces. At twenty he passed the provincial examination, at thirty-two the national examinations, receiving appointment as Collator and Corrector of Texts in the twenty-third year of King Sejong's reign. Through five reigns he advanced slowly to the rank of Commandant, never stooping to seek favor from the powerful. Though he endured many upheavals, calamity never touched him.

    At sixty-two, in the second year of King Seongjong's reign, he received appointment as Director of the Board of Appointments and concurrent Censor, but declined twice when summoned. He retired to his village, asking nothing of the world, spending his days with wine and the company of old men for ten years. Yet whenever someone came from the capital, he would inquire about the king's health. Throughout his life he remained steadfast in filial devotion and brotherly affection, arranging marriages for orphan girls and relieving the destitute. His hidden virtues were many.

    He passed away on the eleventh day of the ninth month in Seonghwa's Gyemyo year, and was buried in the eleventh month at the Suheyon valley northwest of Cheongdo, in the qian direction with kun orientation. He lived to seventy-four.

    His wife, Lady Lee of Yongin, was born on the twenty-fourth day of the second month of Yongle's Gapchin year. She was graceful and virtuous from youth. After marrying into the Kim family, she conducted herself with perfect propriety, never showing jealousy toward concubines. Her parents-in-law praised her obedience, and the clan revered her.

    She passed away on the twenty-ninth day of the third intercalary month of the ninth year of Hongzhi, and was buried to the left of her husband in the fifth month, forming a double grave. From her first marriage to Lady Jeong came one daughter. From her marriage to Master Kim came two daughters and three sons. The eldest daughter married an official, the second married another. The two eldest sons both passed the highest examination in Imjin year, and King Seongjong, finding this extraordinary, summoned them to the palace and granted honors to their parents. The youngest son became first in the provincial examination that same year. All three sons eventually served in the central government and sought posts in remote provinces to better support their mother. One generation shared in glory, and the lady received their filial devotion, though she often wept that her husband did not live to see it.

    When parting from her children, she exhorted them to righteousness alone, never weakening in dignity. She taught her three sons to guard their words and deeds, to honor their oaths, and to serve the throne as they served friends. When they went to govern the people, she would say: "Let no complaint reach the ears of your aged mother." With such earnest counsel she sent them forth. When their friends and officials passed through, none failed to pay respects, and she received them as she would her own sons, maintaining strict family discipline yet treating relatives with warmth.

    After her husband's death, she redeemed all his illegitimate sons with her own resources, raising them to free status and providing for their livelihoods. The middle son died as Assistant Judge; the eldest became magistrate of Hamyang; the youngest became Chamberlain of the Board of Revenue. When he resigned to attend his mother's illness, which deepened from slight complaint to grave affliction, her mind remained clear through her failing breath. She managed household affairs without error.

    When her son the magistrate sent for medicine iron from the provincial stores, she heard of it and reproved him: "Should public goods remain in a private home? My illness must not burden your official conduct." She had him return it at once. She arranged her own coffin and grave goods, sewed her own burial garments, distributed the remainder to her servants, and told her two sons: "I am old; death is my fate. Do not grieve and damage your health for me."

    She lived to seventy-three. As the burial approached, her sons, weeping, asked me for this epitaph.

    Alas, though I never received instruction from the Censor, I have long heard of his accumulated virtue and righteous deeds. Through friendship with his three sons, I came to revere their mother as my own. How could I now ascend and bow before her empty place? Thus I write through tears:

    *Epitaph:*

    Ah, our Master, steadfast and noble,
    Broad-minded and resolute,
    Filial and devoted to kinship—
    His conduct was without peer.

    Clean in refusing advancement,
    He lingered as a minor official,
    Shook out his robes and returned,
    His home no more than a small measure.

    In rivers and lakes he dwelt,
    Finding joy in village wine,
    Yet had an inner support—
    Accumulation grew ever greater.

    No reward need be sought;
    Fitting that his line prospers.
    He held the nation's treasure,
    And great things came to pass.

    Early advancement brought renown;
    His teaching was sublime.
    Together in one grave they rest,
    Mutual guardians evermore.

    On stone we carve this record,
    That glory shall not fade.
  footnotes:
    - King Suro (首露王) was the legendary founder of Gaya, the ancient Korean kingdom. The Kim clan of Gimhae traced their ancestry to him.
    - The examination system mentioned (provincial examination, national examination, highest examination) refers to the civil service examinations of the Joseon Dynasty.
    - The positions mentioned (Director of Board of Appointments, Censor, magistrate, chamberlain) were significant bureaucratic posts in the Joseon government.
    - The practice of 'retiring in honor' while declining further appointments reflects the Confucian ideal of the virtuous official who serves according to principle rather than ambition.
